The paper deals with algorithmic game theory and proposes a method to reduce the computational complexity of large games by decomposing them into smaller components. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The method involves identifying interaction graphs among players and decomposing players' interactions into linear combinations of games, which involves techniques from linear algebra and graph theory. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. The paper also deals with social systems and real-world problems, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a method to find a consistent equilibrium, which involves techniques from artificial intelligence and optimization, suggesting that it may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
